content_x: 萬五員工人心惶惶 友邦急召近百總監解畫 (明報)2010年3月2日 星期二 05:10 【明報專訊】對本港的保誠及友邦合共超過1.5萬名員工和經紀來說，昨日如坐針氈，人心惶惶。傳媒廣泛報道兩家公司合併的消息，有友邦中層人士稱先感到驚訝，然後是迷惘。友邦於昨午便急召近百名區域總監返總部開會，有高層形容兩家公司日後的運作如匯豐及恒生一樣，各用自己的品牌獨立運作。  將來獨立運作 一如匯豐恒生  據了解，友邦昨日召集區域總監開會，講解合併後情况。會上有總監表示，擔心保誠收購後會改掉友邦這品牌。不過，有友邦管理層分析，友邦及英國    保誠兩個品牌將會同時存在，猶如匯豐及恒生保險運作一樣。至於兩家公司的優劣，他指保誠在傳統人壽產品較為出色，而友邦在投資相連及儲蓄產品上有較大優勢。另一方面，友邦在本港未有開拓銀行銷售，反之保誠早已與渣打合作，故此在銀行銷售上，友邦會得益。  另外，兩公司的商業文化也需要時間磨合。保誠行政總裁容佳明早前接受本報訪問時稱，從工作了13年的友邦過檔保誠，發現美資企業與英資企業的文化確有不同，保誠的銷售代理較斯文，所以他會不斷接觸他們，傳授更「活潑」的銷售方法。  合併事件另一戲劇性發展，是統帥容佳明的轉變。他本身是友邦香港一哥，在金融海嘯發生後，母公司美國    國際集團出現財困，令到香港友邦出現斷單潮，業績一落千丈。友邦行政總裁及主席Mark Wilson不滿，在2009年7月時將中國區總裁陳榮聲接替容佳明做香港及澳門    友邦一哥，以鋪排友邦本港上市之路。容佳明於去年10月過檔保誠，豈料風水輪流轉，容日後或有機會統領兩家公司的香港業務。  保誠員工憂反被開刀  今次影響較大的應是後勤人員，友邦一名中層人士表示，有些後勤崗位重複而有需要裁員。保誠的後勤員工鄭小姐擔心，保誠員工反而會首先成開刀對象，「老闆（容佳明）是A記過檔，一定對前公司有感情㗎，我口地只係同佢相處了幾個月，第日要炒人，多數揀我口地啦！」英國保誠有達千多名後勤人員，而友邦只有800人左右。對友邦前線銷售人員來說，合併反而帶來轉機，「我相信顧客對公司會增加信心，上市反而會受股價影響」。  工會：憂一家獨大  香港保險業總工會理事長張偉良收到有業界反映，擔心兩公司合併後，會有一家獨大的情况出現，減少競爭及進步。工會則憂慮併購後會裁員，他們希望兩間公司對員工福利不會有重大改變，並呼籲兩間公司的員工遇有勞工問題，可尋求工會幫助。 .    真喺唔知是禍是福~?~!

content_x: 關于樓主的問題，我本人覺得對 actuarial analyst 來說，general insurance 比 life insurance 多多了。 對好多人來說保險的分類只有 人壽(life)和非人壽(general)。但其實人壽只係保險的其中一項，而非人壽(general)的種類就多好多。除了法定的保險：勞工和汽車，主要還有責任險、工程險、船險、火險、意外險等。General insurance 的產品理論上是可以無窮無盡。從最古老的船險，發展到現在；近幾十年來多了幾種保險，例如飛機險、恐怖主義險、太空險等。這些新保險都需要 actuarial analyst 來計算風險，從而厘定保費。 原有的保險也會隨著時代的變更、保險情況的不同，而需要調整保費。從醫療和科技進步至新車新船新飛機等，都會影響到保費的厘定。這些厘定便需要actuarial analyst 來幫忙。 甚至，有時候一些特殊情況，需要特別度身訂造保險，更需要 actuarial analyst 和他對保險的專業知識，幫客人和保險公司訂造保險產品。  所以，對 actuarial analyst 來說，在general insurance 的發展空間，遠比 life insurance 的多 如果是想做設計或幫保險公司選擇基金產品，那些已經不是 life insurance 的范圍了，是金融那邊了
English: As for the owner of the building, my people think that for practical analyst, general insurance gives life insurance more. For many people, the classification of insurance is only Life (life) and non life (general). But in fact, life is only one of the insurance, and there are many types of non life (general). In addition to the insurance of workers and automobiles, there are mainly liability insurance, engineering insurance, ship insurance, fire insurance, accident insurance, etc In theory, there are endless products. From the oldest ship insurance to the present, several kinds of insurance have been added in recent decades, such as aircraft insurance, terrorism insurance, space insurance, etc. these new insurance also need to be calculated by practical analysis, so as to determine the premium. Some insurance policies need to be adjusted according to the changes of the times and the discord of insurance situation. The latest car, new ship, new aircraft, etc. of medical and technological progress will also affect the percentage of insurance premium. These percentages still need the help of practical analyst. Sometimes, some special situations require special tailor-made insurance, but also need the actual analyst He has a professional knowledge of insurance and can help customers and insurance companies tailor-made insurance products. Therefore, for practical analyst, the development space of general insurance is far more than that of life insurance. content_x: 回應： 我也是做GI，做broker。在quote價的時候發現保險公司每年會因應風險而改變價錢。比如說 車會因為某類車容易撞或上一年被偷得多，或者某類工作上一年容易受傷，會因此提高保費。  保費的調整、定價，尤其是GI，保險公司做決定的通常有三種： 1. 用同行保費作指標；這樣的actuarial analyst的作用就相對細左，因為 underwriters 靠的是市場價格，而不是 actuarial analysist 建議價格 2. 在新東西出來的時候，比如說新車，沒有什么記錄，underwriters也難定價。這個時候就要靠 actuarial analyst 來分析車行歷史和出來後一段時間內實行定價。因為市場上沒有指標 3. 再保險公司 (Re-insurer)在定保費，其實占的比重根多。他們要利用actuarial analyst 來計算某類保險的賠償情況，收取保險公司保費。再保險保費的調整，往往會令到保險公司增加保費，所謂羊毛出在羊身上...  另外，如果沒有actuarial analyst，保險公司就沒有指標厘定保費，很容易因此而令保險公司 因賠償過多而“爆煲”。Actuarial analyst 的作用，最低限度，就是給 underwriters 建議，建議他們不要把價錢調到太低。以免影響到保險公司的健康。  所以我覺得actuarial analyst 在保險業中的地位還是挺高的，縱使他們不是做什么生意。

content_x: 替你澄清這一點 保誠背後是沒有這樣的儲備,所以才需要供股集資 210億美元 就今次告吹了的交易,成本使咗 4億幾英鎊,即6億幾美元     UPDATE 5-UK's Prudential ends $35.5 bln Asian takeover bidWed Jun 2, 2010 5:15am EDT            Prudential Plc PRU.L 560.00p -15.50-2.69% 6:07pm UTC+0800     * Failed transaction costs $659 million      * Pru CEO, chairman under fire, Pru future unclear  * Exit clears way for IPO of AIG's Asian unit  * Pru shares fall by nearly 3 pct in London trade (Adds comments, London share price)  By  and Denny Thomas  HONG KONG, June 2 (Reuters) - Britain's Prudential ([url=/finance/stocks/overview?symbol=PRU.L][/url]) has abandoned its plan to buy AIG's Asian life unit AIA for $35.5 billion, bowing to shareholder criticism over the price it had agreed to pay and leaving its management under fire.  Prudential's move on Wednesday was widely expected after bailed-out U.S. giant American International Group ([url=/finance/stocks/overview?symbol=AIG.N][/url]) refused to cut the price, turning down a last-ditch effort from Britain's largest insurer to simultaneously appease shareholders' concerns over price and seal the deal.  "We listened carefully to shareholders over the price and initiated a renegotiation of the terms with AIG. Unfortunately, it has not been possible to reach agreement," Prudential Chairman Harvey McGrath said in a statement.  "We are therefore withdrawing from the transaction."  For AIG the collapse of the sale means it must weigh up its options which include a potential return to its previous plan to float off American International Assurance (AIA) with a record initial public offering that was once reckoned to be worth up to $15 billion.  For Prudential, however, the end of the botched takeover effort left its strategy open to question, with both Chief Executive Tidjane Thiam and McGrath seen as having personally spearheaded the plan that would have made it Asia's largest foreign-owned insurer.  Both will spend much of Wednesday speaking to the insurer's top investors, smoothing ruffled feathers and hoping to dampen revived talk of a break-up of Britain's top insurer.  They will also have to explain away the hefty, including a break-up fee, the impact of currency hedging and other costs.  "Management are in a very difficult position given the turn of events that have unfolded. We would like them to set out the strategy for the next one to three years and then make a judgment from there," one top investor told Reuters.  Prudential's London-listed shares jumped on news of the likely withdrawal on Tuesday, but were down 3 percent at 558 pence by 0900 GMT on Wednesday.    SHAREHOLDERS TO MEET  Prudential's retreat will mean it has avoided a highly embarassing public defeat at the hands of shareholders, who were due to vote next Monday on the deal and a $21 billion rights issue to help fund it. [ID:nTOE64U07Y]  Shareholders will still meet next week, however, in a gathering that is now expected to provide the first opportunity for many to quiz management on what went wrong, and why.  One key question will be how long Thiam, in the top job at the Pru for less than a year, can remain at the helm.  "The risk is the company is rudderless, lacking leadership," analyst Marcus Barnard at Oriel Securities said. "They have incurred a net 450 million of costs, after the effect of currency hedging which would probably have given them between 300 and 500 million of pounds -- so you have  and you have nothing to show for it. It's a tough one."  Thiam, a former Ivory Coast government minister, was toasted in the industry when he was named as chief executive, but his execution of the Asian deal has been widely criticised as flawed. Investors and analysts have pointed to errors including a regulatory hitch that caused an unprecedented delay in launching a rights share offer this month.  Thiam had argued the AIA deal would give the 162-year-old British insurer a rare opportunity to grab a commanding presence in Asia. But shareholders said the deal was simply too costly, pointing to the risks associated with integrating employees of two fierce insurance rivals in Asia.  Prudential ([url=/finance/stocks/overview?symbol=2378.HK][/url]) said it would not proceed with the planned rights offering in London and Hong Kong.
